I don&#39;t know where you get your dates from, but assuming you can make an array out of them easily enough; I think a custom sort function would do the trick. Of course, you might get more elegant code using Date objects, but since there are only three sorting criteria, I don&#39;t see the point of over-engineering. This is the code I came up with :

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    //test case date array
    let dates = [&quot;15-Dec-2015&quot;, &quot;23-Feb-2029&quot;, &quot;14-Apr-2009&quot;, &quot;15-Apr-2009&quot;, &#39;15-May-2009&#39;, &#39;14-Apr-2004&#39;];

    //custom sorting
    let sortedDates = dates.sort((a, b) =&gt; { //compare function
    	const monthArray = [&#39;Jan&#39;, &#39;Feb&#39;, &#39;Mar&#39;, &#39;Apr&#39;, &#39;May&#39;, &#39;Jun&#39;, &#39;Jul&#39;, &#39;Aug&#39;, &#39;Sep&#39;, &#39;Oct&#39;, &#39;Nov&#39;, &#39;Dec&#39;]; //month index
      //split a and b
    	a = a.split(&#39;-&#39;); 
