answers.body_markdown:
The issue is that [`getElementsByClassName`][1] is a **live** `HTMLCollection`. When an element no longer matches (because you&#39;ve removed the class), it&#39;s removed from the collection:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const list = document.getElementsByClassName(&quot;example&quot;);
    console.log(list.length);       // 2
    console.log(list[0].innerHTML); // &quot;A&quot;
    list[0].classList.remove(&quot;example&quot;);
    console.log(list.length);       // 1
    console.log(list[0].innerHTML); // &quot;B&quot;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;example&quot;&gt;A&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;example&quot;&gt;B&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

This means that if you&#39;re doing a loop and operate on the first entry, then increment your index, you&#39;ll miss what used to be the second entry because it&#39;s the first entry now.

A couple of ways to fix that:

1. Loop backward, or
2. Convert the `HTMLCollection` into an array before starting, or
3. Use [`querySelectorAll`][2] to get a **snapshot** `NodeList` instead, so that the lists contents don&#39;t change while you&#39;re updating.

Here&#39;s an example removing the classes `red` and `bold` from a series of elements using `querySelectorAll` so the `NodeList` is static:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: true console: false babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    setTimeout(() =&gt; {
        const list = document.querySelectorAll(&quot;.red, .bold&quot;);
        for (let n = 0; n &lt; list.length; ++n) {
            list[n].classList.remove(&quot;red&quot;);
            list[n].classList.remove(&quot;bold&quot;);
        }
    }, 800);

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .red {
        color: red;
    }
    .bold {
        font-weight: bold;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;red&quot;&gt;red 1&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;bold&quot;&gt;bold 1&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;red bold&quot;&gt;red 2 and bold 2&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;bold&quot;&gt;bold 3&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;bold&quot;&gt;bold 4&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

----

See also [my answer here](https://stackoverflow.com/a/46929259/157247): `NodeList` is now officially *iterable*, meaning you should be able to use a `for-of` loop on it. That answer shows how to polyfill that on slightly-older environments that haven&#39;t implemented it yet. It also shows how to add iterability to `HTMLCollection` (but note that `HTMLCollection` is **not** specified to be iterable).

  [1]: https://dom.spec.whatwg.org/#dom-document-getelementsbyclassname
  [2]: https://dom.spec.whatwg.org/#dom-parentnode-queryselectorall

